<BLOCKQUOTE>
<HR>
Tremelo-1018-Prexus wrote:<BR>"<EM>I mentioned this on another thread.</EM></FONT>
<DIV></FONT></DIV><EM>You can use the macros for MOST of your keys.&nbsp; Then have 1 hotkey that you actually link directly to the Song list.</EM>"</FONT>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>And the conclusion was: When you macro&nbsp;3 songs + clicky&nbsp;and add the extra stop-key, you come to a 5 button twist vs having a 7 button twist non-macro'd.&nbsp; Not only is it awkward but it only slightly decrease the number of keys pushed.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>Now, what happens when you add in 2 clickies (common use would be lute &amp; horn)?&nbsp; Care to map that out with using a different key to stop songs?</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>There's 2 points you are missing.</DIV>
<DIV>1. Macros are a <U>workaround </U>for a poor interface.&nbsp;&nbsp;The UI&nbsp;should be flat out fixed.</DIV>
<DIV>2. Cliky items should work like songs (ie. they should be stoppable &amp; should stop other songs).</DIV><BR>
<HR>
</BLOCKQUOTE><BR>
<DIV></DIV>
<P>I'm sorry, apparently my first post was unclear.&nbsp; I said nothing about having an extra stop key.&nbsp; I just said that you don't macro 1 song.&nbsp; Link that 1 song directly to the hotkeys as you already do with all your songs.&nbsp; Then you only have to double tap 1 song.&nbsp; The other songs you can tap once.&nbsp; The one song just happens to double as a stopsong key, just like any other song that is linked directly.</P>
